I hope DocDel is safe and out of harms way. I have read his past posts and he seems to be a honorable individual with a big heart. From one medic to another, hang in there with the rehab! I had a heart attack at 34 that was like a warning shot over my bow. Nothing like you are going through but I can relate. My thoughts are with you.<br><br>
Doc Spatz. Sorry for the assumption that you were a medical doc. You might as well be with the amount of time you've had in clinic! GEEZ!<br>
Likewise I was not a CO medic. And when I left the firebase I was armed to the hilt, Zinn was not. I carried enough for both of us including a 45 colt automatic with tracers and a grenade launcher with high explosive and buckshot rounds. Both were weapons that could be fired with one hand if need be. And be assured none of us wore a red cross on our helmet.The NVA could recognize your first aid bag well enough. <br>
In response to the many homeless Vietnam vets. What can I say? In part you&quot;re right. Walking wounded, delayed emotional trauma. Does it really matter the predicament they are in as it does how and why they got there. My oldest brother is a Vietnam Era vet. We have not heard from him in 5 or more years. I to this day don't know why he chose that path. But he did and wants to be left alone. Also Doc, there are alot of homeless that claim to be Vietnam Vets when they are not, for obvious reasons. Society tagged us as loosers and the rest is history. But remember in the early 80's with the advent of all the Vietnam movies that came out? Then it was &quot;fashionable&quot; to know a Vietnam vet, ie the cardboard signs and people other than the homeless mind you, who were not Vietnam vets were exposed to their humiliation and shame. To them I say Nanner Nanner Nan-Naner! You're not a draft dodger and I am certainly not a looser- Vietnam or otherwise. I use Vietnam as a building block in my life, one of those little packages you keep wrapped up in the back of your mind and take it out when needed. I say to myself &quot; Bacsi me boy you made it out of Vietnam, you can get through this one&quot;.<br>
Everyone at some point has to do some soul searching and become personably accountable for what he or she might have said. I believe you have done that. Everyone and I mean everyone has a Mariah. There is no one on the planet that likes a few belts of bourbon more than me. Why I'll have you know I am a registered member of the Rare Breed Society(Wild Turkey&quot;s Barrel Batch). But next time you feel the urge to vent, the best advice I can give you is build a fire, get your family around you and stare at the fire. After about a hour go ahead and invite John Daniels over for a short visit. Works for me. <br>
Socrates was the gadfly to greek society. He evoked reaction and made people think. Your not Socrates and who would want to be! But you are certainly the gadfly of the site. No offense intended, hopefully none taken. Try not to make enemies and be happy in life, for you are a longer time dead.<br><br>
Bacsi        <br><br>
